This whole restaurant chain currently owned by Chris Birkinshaw and is responsible for trying to prevent Native Hawaiian businesses and restaurants from using the HAWAIIAN phrase "Aloha Poke" in their business names. The audacity, having a white owned business trying to forbid people from even being able to use words from Their Culture and Language in Their own family owned businesses. The forced other businesses in the area to rebrand their shops, something that is not a quick and easy process, because they so badly wanted to hoard this title to themselves. These small family businesses were forced to comply with Aloha Poke's demands. There was never really serious, genuine cooperation. There is no real "choice" here. If they did not do this they face the threat of a major chain restaurant suing them and that could cost thousands more to small, sometimes struggling, local business owners. It's a blatant disrespect to a whole group of people who have already suffered the theft and appropriation of other parts of their culture  and this "branding" practice only shows the company's blatant tone deaf attitude and insensitivity to respecting Hawaiian culture.
Won't support any company, let alone a chain on the mainland that trademarks hawaiian words and threatens local hawaiian businesses that existed before them.

I love sushi. I love the idea of deconstructed sushi in a bowl. I also love that I can order as many toppings as I want and it's included in the price. However, I feel that for the price, there could be a bit more quality and consistency. The first time I ordered avocado as a topping, it was diced alongside the other ingredients. Subsequent visits I get a small spoonful of avocado - a single piece - often found at the bottom of my bowl. Sometimes I get orange tobiko, sometimes black. Sometimes the bowl is packed to the brim, other times, I get mostly rice. I try asking for the small sized price in the medium sized bowl, but they don't all the time acknowledge my request. Finally, I really wish there was one of those frequent diner punch cards, for as often as I stop by, it would be nice to get a small discount once in a while.

Aloha has really gone downhill in my opinion. I used to love going here, but recently it feels like the quality has really degraded.  My "big" salmon bowl today had maybe 6-7 small chunks of fish in it, and seemed to be 70-80% rice. I ended up throwing away about half a bowl of rice, when I used to easily and happily finish the whole thing.  I also recently got a very bad case of food poisoning after eating here, although it's impossible to know for sure if it was the raw salmon or something else. I'm usually the person with an iron-stomach that never gets sick, so it was definitely weird.  Anyway, food poisoning or not, I'm don't want to continue paying over $10 for a bowl of rice with a fish garnish.

Are you wondering if the lunch line at Aloha Poke is worth the wait? This was the question I asked myself when I arrived at the French Market, starving and freezing from my walk. The idea of waiting more than three minutes to start stuffing my face was enough to make me swoon with hunger. However, the line snaking its way around the aisles seemed like a pretty good testament to the food. Squaring my shoulders, I braved the line. Thankfully, the staff was fast and efficient, and the wait wasn’t too long after all. I decided on the middle-sized bowl, confusingly called the Big. For the poke, I went with the naked ahi. One thing I really loved about Aloha is that you can choose as many toppings as you want without having to pay extra. You can even get the 808, which is all the toppings. I got edamame, ginger, scallions, pineapple, and avocado. All the ingredients were extremely fresh. I’m always a little wary about getting avocado at restaurants since it browns so quickly, but the avocado topping my bowl was green and pretty. The sesame vinaigrette was light and tasty (so tasty, in fact, that I’ve been trying recreate it at home, but it’s never quite the same). I encourage you to brave the lunch line at Aloha. It’s definitely worth it.

Pretty good I must say for a brand new Poke pop-up right here in the heart of Chicago, located in the French Market.  I created my own & selected the Big (16oz) size for $9.50 with brown rice & salad for the base, the marinated salmon, and tobiko, avacado, crunch, & seaweed salad for the toppings (unlimited topping choices btw).  The salmon was fresh, cold, big cubed pieces.

Aloha Poke is located in Chicago's French Market. This build-your-own Poke spot is by far my favorite place in the French Market. I ordered the Kahuna size bowl and had marinated tuna on a bed of greens and added various different toppings and sauces. The result of my creation was like having a giant bowl of deconstructed sushi rolls and it absolutely blew my mind! It was so fresh and delicious! Aloha is new to the French Market and has gained a huge following since they opened not very long ago. I got there just after 11:30 on a Wednesday and there was already a line stretching down the aisle. The line moved rather quickly, but I noticed that as I waited, it continued to grow and had doubled in size by the time I got my food. I suggest getting there early if trying to go during the weekday lunch hours. The prices were acceptable for the generous portions offered. I will be back....probably more often than I should!
